description.plain:
A California native, Ashe has been turning heads with her balance of modern day pop writing and vintage vocals. Having graduated in composition & production from the world renowned Berklee College of Music, Ashe gained international exposure as a songwriter and jazz vocalist soon after.

She quickly gained notoriety in the electronic space after collaborating with the likes of Louis the Child, Whethan, Shaun Frank, Ben Phipps and many more. After accumulating more than 75 million Spotify streams, 8 #1 Hype Machines in a row and charting #1 on the Spotify Global Viral 50, Ashe inked deals with Mom + Pop Music, SONGS music publishing and Paradigm Talent Agency to release her debut solo track “Used to It.” Performances at Coachella and Red Rocks with Big Gigantic and a run of dates on The Chainsmokers arena tour alongside Shaun Frank and Whethan cemented Ashe’s presence in the electro-pop side.

Ashe released her debut EP, The Rabbit Hole, in June 2018.

Ashe released her debut studio album, Ashlyn, on May 7, 2021.

songs.title: Moral of the Story

description.plain:
“Moral of the Story” is Ashe’s farewell to a past relationship. It is the first release since her debut EP, The Rabbit Hole and the title track to her two-part EP series.

The track saw its peak in early February 2020, almost a year after its initial release, when it was featured in a pivotal scene in the teen Netflix film To All The Boys 2: P.S. I Still Love You. Genius said in its own article that the song “saw an immediate spike on Genius, skyrocketing from 268 [daily] pageviews to 13,152 overnight.”

description.plain:
Niall Horan hops on the remix to Ashe’s hit song “Moral of the Story,” taken from her two-part EP under the same name.

Ashe first teased the remix on June 12, 2020 when she posted a screenshot of her and the mystery feature on a FaceTime call to her social medias. The next day, after a plethora of fan speculation, she confirmed the feature was, in fact, Niall Horan.

songs.title: Save Myself

description.plain:
“Save Yourself” serves as a spiteful response to her hit April 2019 single “Moral of the Story” and its success being birthed from her divorce.

This anger Ashe expresses in the song, which weaves its way throughout the lyrics, serves as a “sobering reminder” about the nightmare of the relationship with her ex-husband. By freeing all of her pent up angry feelings towards her then-partner, as well as to herself for ignoring the signs, she is saving herself now when she could not free herself from back then as quickly as she could have.
